	   				   			<p>by <strong>Natalie</strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>05 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-222093">16:27</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ac5b517f0b6f5f26cca41bd8ee810c98?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>This is kind of long, so I won&#8217;t be at all offended if you don&#8217;t respond, or don&#8217;t respond right away.  It&#8217;s partially me just thinking things through as I write.</p>
<p>Thank you for posting this!  Interesting to see it tie in a bit with some of the things I&#8217;m studying in my college classes, such as gender roles in the Yoruba (and some other African groups) being contingent upon qualities such as age, seniority, whether or not a woman is a mother, whether or not she is postmenopausal, insider/outsider, etc. (the class is about women in African history).  </p>
<p>You write that: &#8220;He talks about “wealth,” which is the access to material resources, typically thought of as financial. Now, confusingly, he calls this “Class,” which is unfortunate terminology.&#8221;  This made me wonder, how much of a correlation do you see between Class and Stand?  In German history before Weber&#8217;s time (e.g. nineteenth century), when there were still absolutist rulers, you had situations where, for example, a businessman from the bourgeoisie could be extremely wealthy, whereas an aristocrat could be not-very well off, yet would still have the status (Stand) of being an aristocrat.  If you were to divide people in The Scene (or at least those that engage with the Scene to some degree) into two vague categories of those of greater and lesser Stände, do you think The Scene could be described similarly, or are there more barriers preventing those with lesser Stände from gaining Class/capital?</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   	<li class="clear" id="comment-222122">
    	<div class="comment byuser comment-author-maymay bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://maybemaimed.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>maymay</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>05 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-222122">17:37</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/39ece444504f8db7c07c1a6c42345a82?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<blockquote cite="#comment-222093"><p>…how much of a correlation do you see between Class and Stand?</p></blockquote>
<p>A lot, <a href="#comment-222093" rel="nofollow">Natalie</a>, but it depends on the scope of your view. The entire Scene-State populace is overwhelmingly white and middle(-upper)-class; it&#8217;s basically a society within a society, so if you don&#8217;t isolate it from the society of which it is a part, you can get distracted by focusing on Class. But in The Scene-State, where there&#8217;s a relatively far smaller distribution of Class/wealth, the amount of material goods you have (while still important) is not nearly as important as Stände. For example, a wealthy person with a huge number of toys but who has a bad reputation (low Stände) will have a harder time playing than a well-connected (high social network capital) person with a great reputation (plus high Stände) with no toys at all.</p>
<p>So there is a correlation, but since The Scene-State is run essentially as an oligarchy, it is more accurate to think of it as a society more like Germany before Weber&#8217;s time than today&#8217;s lowercase-d democratic institutions. The one salient exception is that the accrual of power (Weber&#8217;s &#8220;social resources&#8221;) is far more sensitive to positions of Stände than Class; i.e., social capital is more important than financial capital in this subcultural environment.</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-222093"><p>If you were to divide people in The Scene (or at least those that engage with the Scene to some degree) into two vague categories of those of greater and lesser Stände, do you think The Scene could be described similarly[…]?</p></blockquote>
<p>Yes, I do. At least, I think I do, if I understand your question correctly. :) Please let me know if I&#8217;m misunderstanding your question. (You probably have a greater understanding of German history than I do.)</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   	<li class="clear" id="comment-222136">
    	<div class="comment even thread-even depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong>qp</strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>05 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-222136">17:57</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/9a7fb1738daaf7d6394968fb049dab9b?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>This is a fascinating post and I think I need to check out those ethnographies. The discussion of the play economy in The Scene is a very good framework for my experiences and observations. Even when I was involved in it, I was partnered and pretty much monogamous, and so was not looking to find partners for play there. And even so, I gained respect by playing publicly, and I think more respect by topping publicly than I would have gotten from bottoming in the same situation. Which was weird to me, because&#8230; why did the play I have matter when I was actively not looking for more? </p>
<p>I&#8217;ve moved since then and am not really interested in finding my local scene&#8211;I have kinky friends who understand my viewpoint, I&#8217;m still partnered, and if I want to differently explore physical power dynamics (and probably attendant drama, too, but I&#8217;m enough of a newbie to not run into that too much), I&#8217;m finding that martial arts are pretty awesome.</p>
