   	<li class="clear" id="comment-222144">
    	<div class="comment byuser comment-author-maymay bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://maybemaimed.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>maymay</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>05 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-222144">18:21</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/39ece444504f8db7c07c1a6c42345a82?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<blockquote cite="#comment-222136"><p>This is a fascinating post […]. The discussion of the play economy in The Scene is a very good framework for my experiences and observations.</p></blockquote>
<p>Thanks, <a href="#comment-222136" rel="nofollow">qp</a>. I&#8217;m glad my way of explaining things articulates other people&#8217;s experiences and not just my own, too. I&#8217;ve spoken to so many people who have felt these effects but I&#8217;m always a little afraid that I didn&#8217;t <a href="https://twitter.com/relsqui/status/120042081296187392" rel="nofollow">find the right words</a> or, even if I did, that I didn&#8217;t put them in the right order.</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-222136"><p>I think I need to check out those ethnographies.</p></blockquote>
<p>I agree; they are superb. I&#8217;d also urge you to listen to <a href="http://kinkontap.com/?p=1803" rel="nofollow">Staci Newmahr&#8217;s interview on Kink On Tap</a>, which was personally important to me and also incredibly interesting. Follow the rest of the links in my post, above, and you&#8217;ll find references to Weiss&#8217;s work, Wilkinson&#8217;s writings, and so on.</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-222136"><p>Even when I was involved in it, I was partnered and pretty much monogamous, and so was not looking to find partners for play there. And even so, I gained respect by playing publicly[…].</p></blockquote>
<p>I had a whole section on Stände/Status as related to being partnered versus being single, because that&#8217;s actually another factor that has significant ramifications based on intersectional categorical privilege, but I cut it out due to complexity and lack of time.</p>
<p>One of the most critical observations I&#8217;ve made in this vein, however, is that being partnered, such as by having some kind of visible relationship even if it&#8217;s &#8220;just&#8221; as (play) partners, makes it easier to acquire the social resource (Scene-State capital) of &#8220;access to play&#8221; and thus it&#8217;s obvious that partnered people find it easier to enter the work-play economy than single people do. This (plus manifestations of Scene-State sexism/domism) is also reflected in, for example, the door costs at parties, particularly <a href="http://status.maymay.net/notice/23373" rel="nofollow">&#8220;femdom&#8221; parties such as the SF Citadel&#8217;s Mystique, where &#8220;unaccompanied submissives&#8221; (single men) are charged more money for admission than partnered men</a>, or else they have to jump through hoops to get into the party at the same rate as others. Therefore, people actually end up partnering up not just to fulfill personal relationship wants, but also because it has a direct effect on one&#8217;s power (in the Weberian sense) in Scene-State environs. Which is, frankly, fucked up and, to stretch a metaphor, a disgusting throwback to arranged marriages.</p>
<p>Anyway…yeah…I still need to work out the right words for taking that tack.</p>
<p>In the mean time, thanks for reading.</p>
	   		</div>
