</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   	<li class="clear" id="comment-232066">
    	<div class="comment even thread-even depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://blog.ceciliatan.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Cecilia Tan</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>24 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-232066">14:41</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/38252bf8249caa9bd1dc3fc41ca07da9?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>This post couldn&#8217;t have come at a better time, when I&#8217;ve got friends and acquaintances trying to figure out where they/we fit in the Occupy movement, and trying to make that leap from specific issues to larger understanding of how we create power structures that oppress ourselves. </p>
<p>This comment could easily grow to be as long as the original talk, because so many things you bring up had me thinking &#8220;oh, yes, and that ties into this&#8221; &#8220;of course, and that reminds me of that&#8221; etc&#8230; If I blather on, however, it&#8217;ll just dilute the message. Two things I will mention:</p>
<p>1) I was staggered the first time I heard a panel at Leather Leadership Conference on how submissives felt ignored, put- down, not listened to, etc. when they tried to take part in structures like the boards of directors of various leather/BDSM community groups. First I had disbelief/denial: &#8220;Really? Are you kidding me? Can people be that stupid/bad/ridiculous? That can&#8217;t be everywhere&#8230; &#8221; Then anger: &#8220;What the f*** is wrong with those doms?&#8221; Then bargaining: &#8220;Maybe if we keep having panels like this, and workshops and consciousness raising seminars, we can reverse this tide, educate dickweeds,&#8221; etc&#8230; Then cynicism/depression: &#8220;What&#8217;s the point? These dickweeds are never going to change and I&#8217;m tired of having to even think about it anymore.&#8221; yeah, I know, these are the first four stages of grief, and the fifth one is acceptance. But I won&#8217;t accept that &#8220;this is just human nature&#8221; anymore than I would accept racist bullshit (for example) from a fellow activist, so why should I accept people acting like some socially inculcated misogynist/anti-submissive bullshit is OK? I shouldn&#8217;t, and no one should, and thank goodness for talks like this one that drag it out into the light. </p>
<p>I&#8217;m a mixed-race bisexual switch and I came into the BDSM/leather community when the Internet was still very small, and the &#8220;establishment&#8221; such as it was seemed to be full of complaints that the bisexual switches were &#8220;taking over&#8221; their (previously sacrosanct) spaces and institutions. Interestingly enough this complaint came from both the strictly gay &amp; lesbian sides of things and from the &#8220;pansexual&#8221; groups like TES, Black Rose, &amp; the like. I don&#8217;t remember seeing much published that said this, but lots of comments (and flame wars) on Usenet and email mailing lists like SM-ACT. I took it all to mean &#8220;Great! Bisexual switches ARE taking over, and therefore this community has a place for me!&#8221; In the Boston area where I was coming out, the previous &#8220;establishment&#8221; groups were all dying off, in fact, so I was part of a bunch of 20-somethings who &#8211;without knowing better&#8211; just started building our own groups, structures, clubs, etc. etc. We had no money but we had that Generation X ideal that one&#8217;s &#8220;career&#8221; was really just a day job and fulfillment of self and life purpose was going to come through avocation, whether hobby or activism or whatever. A lot of the early folks I interacted with came not out of &#8220;leather&#8221; activism, but from Queer Nation, and ACT UP, and the Bisexual Resource Center. And a lot of us came from yet a different subculture, from science fiction fandom, which already existed sociologically as a place where challenging the status quo was expected as part and parcel of the identity. </p>
<p>When NELA got started (then as NLA:New England), we were a bunch of bisexual switches, basically, with a few other identities thrown in, but never enough of one group to overpower the sort of bi switch dynamic that grew culturally to be the group&#8217;s norm. </p>
<p>This is all a long way of saying as an activist I grew up in a leather/BDSM fantasy world that was the kink equivalent of Sesame Street, where we had diversity of race, ethnicity, sexuality, and BDSM identity, balanced by the fact that most of us were muppets who didn&#8217;t fit the &#8220;rules&#8221; for &#8220;normal people&#8221; anyway. So it was kind of mind-blowing to sit there in a room and hear people speaking about highly respected groups whose dysfunction included things like the doms making the decisions and then expecting the subs to do all the work. Or turning to a sub in a board meeting and saying &#8220;Why are you here anyway?&#8221; AND NO ONE ELSE IN THE MEETING CALLING THEM ON IT. And so on. Oh jeez, I&#8217;m getting mad on that sub&#8217;s behalf all over again, and that panel was probably ten years ago.</p>
<p>It often brings me back to square one, to the &#8220;women&#8217;s lib&#8221; movement (as my mom called it) in the 1970s when I was growing up. My mom was a charter subscriber to Ms. Magazine, and had her &#8220;feminist epiphany&#8221; when I was 2 years old. And I don&#8217;t remember if she said this originally or if it was a quote from Ms. but it went something like this. &#8220;The lesson feminism is trying to teach is not that a WOMAN can be ________ (an astronaut, as strong as a man, President, etc&#8230;) but that ANYONE can be, regardless of their gender.&#8221; Unfortunately, if anything sinks it, it tends to only be the exception, not the generalization. &#8220;Oh that exceptional woman over there, well, she can be a firefighter.&#8221; Which is better than the absolute &#8220;women cannot do ____&#8221;, but misses the point. By merely acknowledging the exception, one continues to uphold the same power structure that made it exceptional in the first place. Now replace &#8220;submissive&#8221; or &#8220;male sub&#8221; or &#8220;bisexual switch&#8221; or WHATEVER thing would seem startling in the example and you have it. </p>
<p>(Note: I&#8217;m not saying role models are not important. A male sub who effectively leads an organization, a female sub who is a powerful spokesperson, just to make up some examples, they can help others to see the gaps in the paradigm and a place for themselves, but again if all we end up with is accepting the &#8220;exceptional case&#8221; the power structure/racism/ domism/sexism is not challenged, but rather upheld.)</p>
<p>Er, I think that was one of the two things I was going to post here, and I don&#8217;t actually remember now what the second was. Probably just thanks for a thought-provoking piece. If THE VELDERET had anything to do with triggering all that, as your tweet implied, then even better. I wrote that book when I was just finishing my masters degree in writing (which included a couple of literature classes on utopia/dystopia), and it was a commission work for a porn magazine called Taste of Latex. What they wanted was a hot, fetishy, kinky sex scene every month. What I wanted was to (gently) poke fun at The Scene and the One True Way people I saw popping up in The Scene then (it was the early 1990s), since I see any kind of rigid orthodoxy in any realm being just Wrong. The result is some folks took some of what I imagined as satire as gospel instead&#8230; I suppose that&#8217;s inevitable, as different readers are always going to read at different levels. The plain truth is that ultimately NONE of the power structures (and therefore erotic structures) shown in the book are free of corruption. However the subtlety that just because my characters get off on something doesn&#8217;t mean it&#8217;s GOOD (or that I approve) might be something that the porn medium just can&#8217;t convey. </p>
<p>Long story short: whether you agreed with me or &#8220;got&#8221; the book or not is irrelevant, if the book got you thinking about this stuff, that is awesome. Awesome awesome awesome. </p>
<p>Now to go and propagate the links to here&#8230;!</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
