   	<li class="clear" id="comment-235669">
    	<div class="comment byuser comment-author-maymay bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://maybemaimed.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>maymay</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>31 Oct 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-235669">18:18</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/39ece444504f8db7c07c1a6c42345a82?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>I&#8217;m really pleased to hear that my talk got you thinking about so much of this stuff, <a href="#comment-232066" rel="nofollow">Cecilia</a>. :) Thanks for your thoughtful comment.</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-232066"><p>Long story short: whether you agreed with me or “got” the book or not is irrelevant, if the book got you thinking about this stuff, that is awesome. Awesome awesome awesome.</p></blockquote>
<p>Sorry to disappoint, but <a href="https://twitter.com/maymaym/status/128540214380593152" rel="nofollow">reading <cite>The Velderet</cite></a> was not what got me thinking about this. I didn&#8217;t start reading the book until after I gave the above talk at Arse.</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-232066"><p>I wrote that book when I was just finishing my masters degree in writing (which included a couple of literature classes on utopia/dystopia), and it was a commission work for a porn magazine called Taste of Latex. What they wanted was a hot, fetishy, kinky sex scene every month. What I wanted was to (gently) poke fun at The Scene and the One True Way people I saw popping up in The Scene then (it was the early 1990s), since I see any kind of rigid orthodoxy in any realm being just Wrong. The result is some folks took some of what I imagined as satire as gospel instead… I suppose that’s inevitable, as different readers are always going to read at different levels. The plain truth is that ultimately NONE of the power structures (and therefore erotic structures) shown in the book are free of corruption. However the subtlety that just because my characters get off on something doesn’t mean it’s GOOD (or that I approve) might be something that the porn medium just can’t convey.</p></blockquote>
<p>Therein lies one of the dangers of intentionally indirect communication, like &#8220;gentle&#8221; poking-fun or satire. I have said this before and I&#8217;ll say it again: when the reality you are satirizing is as bad or worse than your satirical depiction, people will take what you said seriously. <a href="http://maybemaimed.com/2010/11/27/search-for-pictures-of-men-being-submissive-and-you-end-up-seeing-pictures-of-women-being-dominant/" rel="nofollow">I experienced this myself</a> on <a href="http://malesubmissionart.com/post/91850568/an-unimportant-uninteresting-man-is-hidden-behind" rel="nofollow">Male Submission Art&#8217;s &#8220;April fools&#8221;</a> <a href="http://malesubmissionart.com/post/91916170/some-anonymous-masked-guy-stands-against-a-wall-as" rel="nofollow">series</a> a <a href="http://malesubmissionart.com/post/91994257/a-half-dressed-man-stares-across-a-room-at-a-woman" rel="nofollow">couple years ago</a>.</p>
<p>While you—and I use &#8220;you&#8221; to address the general case here, be you an activist-minded erotica/porn author/producer, a politically active &#8220;liberal&#8221;, what have you—may believe that there is a group of people (<a href="http://driftglass.blogspot.com/2010/06/difference-between-centrism.html" rel="nofollow">called &#8220;the middle&#8221; or &#8220;centrists&#8221;</a>) who you can persuade by just pointing out the inconsistencies or absurdities in bigoted arguments, you are more likely to simply be deluding yourself. If you think that, for instance, the mainstream BDSM world is <em>put off</em> by the instances of domism that you&#8217;ve enumerated in your comment, Cecilia, you are as gravely mistaken as if you believe that pointing out racism or sexism in the Tea Party is actually <em>unattractive to the core Republican party&#8217;s activist base</em>.</p>
<p>In fact racism and sexism is actually <em>what they want</em>; it&#8217;s what they are fighting <em>for</em>. And so it becomes <a href="https://twitter.com/maymaym/status/130852674181677057" rel="nofollow">necessary to call out the &#8220;centrists&#8221; as what <em>they</em> are: lazy, socially irresponsible, and stupid</a>.</p>
<p>So I say be careful with the satire. The sheeple will take it as gospel, while the high-power/class elites will simply use it as fuel. Kink, Inc. and most people involved in the BDSM Scene who support them is a perfect example of this double-blind behavior. Call me a humorless activist if you must, but that&#8217;s probably what happened with The Velderet, and that&#8217;s one reason I stopped doing anything even remotely satirical with Male Submission Art.</p>
<p>Since it can&#8217;t be stated strongly or often enough, I&#8217;ll say it yet again. Kink, Inc. needs to be called out as what they are: corporatist, kleptocratic abusers. And the BDSM Scene-State &#8220;centrists&#8221; needs to be called out as what they are: bigoted enablers of their own and others&#8217; abuse.</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
